  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "LQGP0aWnOpOr1vRhvGaeB1cn4b4=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:37.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\nThe core architectural insight enabling the Swarm channel is that the reactor's sync system supports multiple remotes per collection \u2014 each with its own channel, cursors, and push/pull state.\n\n## Evidence\nFrom the source: \"The reactor's sync system supports multiple remotes per collection. Each remote has its own channel, its own cursors, and its own push/pull state. This means a single drive can be synced to BOTH Switchboard AND Swarm simultaneously.\"\n\nIn `sync_cursors`, a single collection tracks independent ordinals per remote (e.g., gql remote at ordinal 42, swarm remote at ordinal 38).\n\n## Why it matters\nWithout this property, we would need a custom fan-out layer or a single combined channel. Instead, GQL and Swarm are peers, and either can be added or removed without affecting the other.\n\n## Source\nSwarm Channel Architecture, \"The Core Insight: Two Channels, One Collection\".",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:37.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:37.000Z"
    }
  },
